						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Women-scientists-rewarded-for-outstanding-research" title="Women scientists rewarded for outstanding research " alt="link">Women scientists rewarded for outstanding research </a></h2>

	
					<p>
Women researching topics ranging from malaria to nanotechnology have picked up prizes in the annual 'For Women in Science' awards. Malaria researcher Khadijetou Lekweiry from Mauritania received one of the 15 international fellowships awarded. Lekweiry, a doctoral student at the Cadi Ayyad University in Morocco, studies the Anopheles mosquito to find new ways of tackling the spread of malaria among people in cities. She will use the two-year fellowship to carry out her work at the Institute for Research and Development in Dakar, Senegal. (Source Christina Scott, SciDev.net, 16 March 2009)</p>
							<p><span class="date">24/03/2009</span></p>
