						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Tuna-spawning-grounds-can-help-Coral-Triangle-nations-such-as-Solomon-Islands" title="Tuna spawning grounds can help Coral Triangle nations such as Solomon Islands " alt="link">Tuna spawning grounds can help Coral Triangle nations such as Solomon Islands </a></h2>

	
					<p>








 




  
  

	
	<a href="/var/knowledge/storage/images/media/images/frontpage-uploads/tuna/250891-1-eng-GB/tuna.png" rel="lightbox[]" >	
	  </a>
	
		
			
	
  	






	 
  





	“With climate change threatening to alter habitats in the region, it is even more critical to manage marine ecosystems for the ongoing food security of the region and for the survival of many species that depend on the Coral Triangle’s unique marine environment,” said Dr Pet Soede. The Coral Triangle is the most diverse marine region on the planet, matched in its importance to life on Earth only by the Amazon rainforest and the Congo basin. Defined by marine areas containing more than 500 species of reef-building coral, it covers 5.4 million square kilometers of ocean across six countries in the Indo-Pacific – Indonesia, Malaysia, Papua New Guinea, Philippines, Solomon Islands, and Timor-Leste. World Wide Fund (WWF) is urging tuna fishing nations in the Asia Pacific to use the region’s essential ecosystem services to negotiate better prices and fairer fishing arrangements with foreign fishing nations. (Source: Solomon Star, 15 March 2009)This article is part of the Knowledge for Development <a href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Livestock" target="_blank">dossier on Livestock and Fisheries</a>.</p>
							<p><span class="date">24/03/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Tuna-spawning-grounds-can-help-Coral-Triangle-nations-such-as-Solomon-Islands">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Put-water-centre-stage" title="Put water centre stage " alt="link">Put water centre stage </a></h2>

	
					<p>Unless water occupies a more central role in decisions regarding crises such as climate change and food security, a global water shortage could ensue - leading to political conflict and insecurity, says a new report. It is accompanied by a series of case studies on selected countries including Cameroon, Sudan and Swaziland. It summons leaders in government, the private sector and civil society to put water at the heart of their thinking, stressing water's essential role in achieving sustainable development and the Millennium Development Goals. (Source: Naomi Antony, SciDev.net, 12 March 2009)</p>
							<p><span class="date">24/03/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Put-water-centre-stage">Read more...</a>
</div>
